}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb400 
 The duty of obedience requires a director to avoid committing ultra vires acts, i.e., acts beyond the scope of the [authority] of the corporation as defined by its [articles of incorporation] or the laws of the state of incorporation .... The duty of loyalty dictates that a director must act in good faith and must not allow his personal interests to prevail over the interests of the corporation .... [T]he duty of due care requires [that] a director must handle his corporate duties with such care as an ordinarily prudent man would use under similar circumstances.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F4357692861_ID0ECFAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F4357692861_ID0ECFAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F4357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
4
}}}
\sb200 
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EMFAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EMFAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The duty of obedience served mostly as a natural corollary to the ultra vires doctrine. Just as the corporation was prevented from acting beyond its powers, corporate actors were obligated not to perpetrate such actions--and could be held liable if they did.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F5357692861_ID0EXFAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F5357692861_ID0EXFAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F5357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
5
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Although instances of personal liability were few, the threat was real.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EAGAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EAGAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Corporations, from the beginning and still today, are to engage only in \u8220\'3flawful business\u8221\'3f and thus are not meant to engage in illegality.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F6357692861_ID0EIGAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F6357692861_ID0EIGAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F6357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
6
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Thus, the original ultra vires doctrine not only set the boundaries of corporate power as established by corporate norms, it also recognized that the corporation is powerless to violate non-corporate norms--that is, external law.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F7357692861_ID0ENGAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F7357692861_ID0ENGAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F7357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
7
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The obedience duty called on fiduciaries to not permit corporate illegality.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWGAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWGAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
But as corporate law (and judicial review of corporate actions) moved from questions of corporate power to those of fiduciary duty, the ultra vires doctrine became largely vestigial--and its appendage, the duty of obedience, quietly wilted away. Speaking as if at a memorial service, one commentator stated:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri400 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li700 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri400 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li700 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb400 
The first of these [fiduciary duties], the duty of obedience, is not conceptually interesting and has not generated significant litigation in recent years. It merely requires directors to comply with the pertinent provisions of the articles, bylaws, and state statutory schemes.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F8357692861_ID0EPHAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F8357692861_ID0EPHAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F8357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
8
}}}
\sb200 
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EZHAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EZHAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Today, only a handful of modern sources refer to the duty of obedience in the for-profit corporation, usually as after-thoughts. No modern for-profit corporation case has turned explicitly on the duty of obedience, though a couple of cases have made clear that directors of a subsidiary corporation need not obey directives of the parent corporation.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F9357692861_ID0EEIAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F9357692861_ID0EEIAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F9357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
9
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 More significantly, no Delaware court (the font of modern corporate law) has 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
ever
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 invoked a \u8220\'3fduty of obedience\u8221\'3f in the for-profit corporation.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F10357692861_ID0EKIAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F10357692861_ID0EKIAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F10357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
10
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ERIAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ERIAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1500_461_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1500_461_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*461
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 This is not to say that the obedience duty no longer exists. Recent courts referring to the duty of care and the duty of good faith have made clear that corporate actors cannot consciously violate--or permit the corporation to violate--corporate and non-corporate norms. Beginning with the 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Allis-Chalmers
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 case in Delaware, courts and commentators have accepted that corporate actors may not choose to disregard non-corporate norms, even when such disregard may be profitable for the corporation.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F11357692861_ID0EKJAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F11357692861_ID0EKJAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F11357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
11
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ERJAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ERJAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The landmark 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Caremark
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 case, and the recent judicial foray into the duty of good faith, makes clear that conscious, and even negligent, disregard for non-corporate norms is antithetical to corporate law.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F12357692861_ID0EBKAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F12357692861_ID0EBKAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F12357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
12
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The source of this \u8220\'3fduty\u8221\'3f to ensure corporate compliance from which legal norms springs is unclear, but its existence seems beyond question.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
