{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EKKAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EKKAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
A. Original Duty of Obedience (Corollary to Ultra Vires Doctrine)
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EUKAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EUKAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Corporate law in the United States began as the regulation of corporate powers. Most early corporate law cases turned on whether the corporation was exercising its powers according to the governing statute and its corporate charter. Most early corporate law treatises devoted themselves extensively to questions of ultra vires.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EGLAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EGLAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1500_462_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1500_462_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*462
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In its heyday at the turn of the last century, the ultra vires doctrine provided umbrage for shareholders who sought protection from management excess--whether for acts beyond the power given to the corporation, acts that were illegal, or acts that exceeded the authority conferred by shareholders.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F13357692861_ID0ESLAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F13357692861_ID0ESLAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F13357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
13
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, corporate waste--corporate expenditures lacking business justification--was treated as exceeded power, not failed duty.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F14357692861_ID0EWLAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F14357692861_ID0EWLAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F14357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
14
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E4LAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E4LAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Importantly, the ultra vires doctrine supplied a tool for ensuring corporate compliance with non-corporate norms. As Professor Greenfield pointed out in an article arguing for the revival of the ultra vires doctrine:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri400 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li700 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri400 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li700 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb400 
During the height of the ultra vires doctrine, a corporation\rquote s illegal activities were considered a subset of the larger category of ultra vires activities. In no sense were corporations considered as having the authority to perform illegal activities, even when performed to advance the interest of the firm.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F15357692861_ID0EWMAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F15357692861_ID0EWMAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F15357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
15
}}}
\sb200 
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EANAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EANAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A commonly cited example of the application of the ultra vires doctrine--and its corollary duty of obedience to enforce non-corporate norms--is the 1909 case of 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Roth v. Robertson
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F16357692861_ID0EPNAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F16357692861_ID0EPNAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F16357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
16
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 There a New York court held directors of an amusement park (Coney Island) personally liable for \u8220\'3fhush money\u8221\'3f paid by the corporation to avoid prosecution for violating \u8220\'3fblue laws\u8221\'3f that forbade business on Sunday. The court made clear that the payments were illegal, \u8220\'3fbad in morals,\u8221\'3f and ultra vires.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F17357692861_ID0EWNAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F17357692861_ID0EWNAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F17357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
17
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E4NAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E4NAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The penalty in 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Roth v. Robertson
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, as well as other earlier cases in which directors permitted the corporation to exceed its powers, was personal liability, not merely an injunction against the corporate overreaching. As a 1901 treatise made clear: \u8220\'3fAll of the authorities agree that if the directors ... do or suffer to be done acts which are beyond their powers ... they may be compelled to make good on the loss.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F18357692861_ID0E6OAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F18357692861_ID0E6OAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F18357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
18
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EGPAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EGPAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
B. Abandonment of the Duty of Obedience (Along with Ultra Vires Doctrine)
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EQPAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EQPAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
But then a subtle shift began in corporate law. Instead of talking about directors being personally liable for their unauthorized actions, treatise authors began to talk about the liability of directors for failures to act responsibly--a switch from power to duty. For example, a turn-of-the-century treatise declared that if directors \u8220\'3fattempt 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1500_463_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1500_463_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*463
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 to act beyond their powers, they may be liable to the corporation for mismanagement.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F19357692861_ID0ELQAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F19357692861_ID0ELQAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F19357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
19
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ESQAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ESQAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Another leading treatise marked the change from power to duty, observing in 1894 that \u8220\'3f[n]o one can state with confidence what the law on [the subject of the ultra vires doctrine] is at the present time, still less predict what it will be in the near future.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F20357692861_ID0EDRAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F20357692861_ID0EDRAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F20357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
20
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 In 1927, the same treatise would conclude that the liability of directors for ultra vires acts is grounded on \u8220\'3fviolation of authority, or neglect of duty.\u8221\'3f
}
