{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ECZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ECZAE_1}
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
C. Revival of the Implicit Duty of Obedience (and Ultra Vires Doctrine)
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EMZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EMZAE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The privatization of the corporation failed. The thesis that corporate actors must ensure corporate compliance with internal and external legal norms is again well-established.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F37357692861_ID0EXZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F37357692861_ID0EXZAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F37357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
37
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Not only have courts returned to the ultra vires doctrine to invalidate management power grabs--such as dead-hand poison pills and backdated options--they have made clear corporate actors are bound to ensure compliance with non-corporate legal norms. Corporate statutes also make clear that corporate illegality finds no comfort 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
under corporate law.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, exculpation provisions in Delaware corporations cannot absolve directors from personal liability for \u8220\'3fa knowing violation of law.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F38357692861_ID0ED1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F38357692861_ID0ED1AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F38357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
38
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EK1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EK1AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A revival of the ultra vires doctrine--and implicitly the duty of obedience-- has come as corporate actors have tested the outer limits of managerial power. Recent cases limiting the power of the board to disenfranchise shareholders have used the language of management power, as well as that of fiduciary duty.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F39357692861_ID0EV1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F39357692861_ID0EV1AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F39357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
39
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Likewise, courts looking at backdated options have chastised directors for both breaching their duties of loyalty and disregarding plan limits.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F40357692861_ID0E11AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F40357692861_ID0E11AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F40357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
40
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Implicit in both lines of cases is the notion that corporate actors are bound to follow internal corporate norms.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ED2AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ED2AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Respect for internal corporate norms also undergirds the \u8220\'3freasonable expectations\u8221\'3f doctrine in the close corporation.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F41357692861_ID0EL2AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F41357692861_ID0EL2AE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F41357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
41
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The doctrine, by enforcing non-formalized agreements of majority and minority investors, emanates from the duty of obedience. Party expectations, akin to charter-like limitations placed on the controlling investor at the behest of the minority investor, raise questions not of care or loyalty but instead of obedience. The majority is bound to the parties\rquote  expectations not because the majority is inattentive or uninformed, or because it is necessarily acting selfishly 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_1500_466_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_1500_466_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*466
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 toward the corporation, but because it has violated the agreed-upon internal norms. As Professor Atkinson has noted, \u8220\'3fthe more fundamental duty of obedience is clearly in play here. Once the minority has the majority\rquote s commitment to a particular kind of corporate activity, that commitment must be obeyed. Conversely, departures from the specified corporate activities violate the duty of obedience.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F42357692861_ID0EM3AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F42357692861_ID0EM3AE_1}
