{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0ET3AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0ET3AE_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The revival of a duty of obedience (though not labeled as such) has also arisen in cases that call on corporate actors to ensure compliance with internal and external non-corporate norms. The landmark case of 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In re Caremark International, Inc. Derivative Litigation
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, built on a revived sense of the corporation as social actor, made clear that corporate directors have duties to create and oversee compliance systems--even when there may be no net financial benefit to the corporation.
}
