{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EKMAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EKMAG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Thus, the duty of obedience has come under attack for limiting non-profit adaptability. The Revised Model Nonprofit Corporation Act (RMNCA), for example, does not recognize the duty of obedience in the non-profit corporation, apparently to create symmetry with its for-profit cousin.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F62357692861_ID0EVMAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F62357692861_ID0EVMAG_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F62357692861_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
62
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 But rather than deny the existence of a duty to comply with legal norms--the tack taken by the ALI Principles for for-profit corporations--the RMNCA assumes the duty of obedience is subsumed in the duties of care and loyalty.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F63357692861_ID0EZMAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F63357692861_ID0EZMAG_1}
