{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Looking at the \u8220\'3fcorporatization\u8221\'3f of non-profit governance, a recent commentator concluded:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri400 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li700 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri400 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li700 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb400 
[T]he law should include a legal requirement that directors commit themselves to an organization\rquote s charitable mission .... [S]ome legal requirement is necessary and important because, without it, there is nothing in the law of nonprofit governance that affirmatively requires directors to strive for charitable goals. While loyal and careful governance, as those duties have been defined in the business context, might further a corporation\rquote s mission, I am not convinced that they always will.
}
