{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
The legal contractarian theory:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa0 \sb0 
implies a theory of the role of corporate law: corporate law should merely provide a set of default rules that managers may adopt on behalf of their firms, while leaving managers free to customize their companies\rquote  charters with legally enforceable rights and obligations. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
In the contractarian view, states are seen as competing with one another to attract incorporations by providing corporate law that offers value-enhancing default rules.
\par 
}
}
}
}
